munity embraced this approach, details how the use of such tools played a critical role in educational and reform movements in the United States, Canada, and England, and traces their impact in public and private spaces. Far from being peripheral illustrations of points articulated in written texts or argued in impassioned speeches, these photographs, prints, paintings, exhibitions, "magic lantern" slides, and films were key components of animal advocacy at the time, both educating the general public and creating a sense of shared identity among the reformers.Uniquely focused on imagery from the early days of the animal rights movement and filled with striking visuals, Art for Animals sheds new light on the history and development of modern animal advocacy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAnimal welfarexHistoryy19th century. 0aAnimal welfarexHistoryy20th century. 0aAnimals in art. 0aVisual communicationxHistoryy19th century. 0aVisual communicationxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 19th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311074522140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271081632zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271081632423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271081632.jpg  a978-3-11-074522-1  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK